    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1871-01-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1871-01-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="81" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d81">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 68.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Fish</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                            Blair</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 48.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1871-01-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 21, 1871.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> This Department has received a note from the
                        minister for foreign affairs of Costa Rica, requesting a detail of two
                        scientific engineers for the purpose of surveying a route for a wagon-road
                        or railway between San José and the Atlantic.</p>
                <p>In the note a promise is made that the salaries and expenses of the engineers
                        shall be promptly paid. Inclosed is the reply of the Department under a
                        flying seal which you may close after reading the answer, which you will
                        then deliver to Mr. Montufar.</p>
                <p>You will notice that although his request has been acceded to, the names of
                        the engineers have not yet been determined upon and nothing is said about
                        their compensation and expenses.</p>
                <p>Before they set out, however, it may be prudent that some definite provision,
                        for the latter at least, should be made in advance by that government.</p>
                <pb facs="0464" n="250" xml:id="pg_250"/>
                <p>You will consequently lose no time in endeavoring to mate a satisfactory
                        arrangement upon this point, of the result of which you will apprise the
                        Department.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HAMILTON FISH.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
